revision.text:
__NOTOC__ An '''alumni magazine''' is a [[magazine]] published by a [[university]], [[college]], or other school or by an [[Alumni association|association of a school's alumni]] (and sometimes current students) in order to keep alumni abreast of fellow alumni and news of their university, often with an implicit goal of [[Fundraising#Relationship building|fundraising]].
An emerging version of alumni magazines are unrelated to educational institutions. Instead the intended readers are former employees of a company. An example of this type of alumni magazine is ''MoForever'' magazine of the [[law firm]] of [[Morrison & Foerster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agendanyc.com/work/morrison-foerster-mofo-alumni-magazine|title=Morrison-Foerster-(MoFo) alumni magazine|website=agendanyc.com|accessdate=30 Nov 2016}}</ref>{{refn|group="Note"|The emerging type of alumni magazines for former employees of a company should not be confused with any fictional alumni magazines whose intended readers are former customers of the company (for example, the ''Flown'' magazine, with former passengers of [[Delta Air Lines]] as the target readership, as reported in [[Satire|satirical]] [[newspaper]] ''[[The Onion]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theonion.com/article/delta-launches-alumni-magazine-for-people-who-flew-36639|title=Delta Launches Alumni Magazine For People Who Flew Airline Previously|newspaper=[[The Onion]]|location=Chicago|date=7 Aug 2014|accessdate=30 Nov 2016}}</ref>}}
==History== The oldest alumni magazine in the [[United States]] is ''[[Yale Alumni Magazine]]'', founded in 1891.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yalealumnimagazine.com/about-us|title=About Us|website=yalealumnimagazine.com|publisher=[[Yale University]]|location=New Haven, Connecticut|accessdate=27 Nov 2016}}</ref>
