{{Infobox language family |name=Berta |region=[[Ethiopia]], [[Sudan]] |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |child1=[[Berta language|Gebeto]] |child2=[[Fadashi language|Fadashi]] |child3=[[Undu language|Undu]] |iso3=wti |glotto=bert1248 |glottorefname=Berta }}
The '''Berta languages''', or '''Wetawit''', traditionally considered dialects of a single language, are [[Berta language|Gebeto]] (Berta proper), [[Fadashi language|Fadashi]], and [[Undu language|Undu]]. They are either a small family (or [[language isolate]]) of their own, or a primary branch of the [[Nilo-Saharan]] language family.
Berta has the typical word order [[subject–verb–object]]. It is a [[tone (linguistics)|tonal]] language. It has significantly influenced some of the [[Eastern Jebel languages]]. The Arabic name "Beni-Shangul" (as in the Ethiopian province of [[Benishangul-Gumuz]]) derives from a Berta expression (with ''bele'' "rock/stone" misanalyzed as Arabic ''beni'' "sons").
