{{Infobox language |name= Cabécar |nativename= |pronunciation= |script = [[Latin script|Latin]] |states = [[Costa Rica]] |region = [[Turrialba]] Region ([[Cartago Province]]) |ethnicity = [[Cabécar people]] {{sigfig|9,310|2}} (2000)<ref name=e18/> |speakers = {{sigfig|8840|2}} |date=2000 |ref=e18 |speakers2= 80% monolingual (no date)<ref name=e10>{{e10|cjp}}</ref><!--figure of 7k monolingual is from this %age. Not in e08.--> |familycolor = American |fam1 = [[Chibchan languages|Chibchan]] |fam2 = [[Chibchan languages|Core-Chibchan]] |fam3 = [[Isthmic languages|Isthmic]] |fam4 = [[Isthmic languages|Western Isthmic]] |fam5 = [[Viceitic languages|Viceitic]] |iso3= cjp |glotto=cabe1245 |glottorefname=Cabécar }}
The '''Cabécar language''' is an indigenous American language of the [[Chibchan languages|Chibchan language family]] which is spoken by the [[Cabécar people]] in Costa Rica. Specifically, it is spoken in the inland Turrialba Region of the Cartago Province. 80% of speakers are monolingual;<ref name=e10/> as of 2007, it is the only indigenous language in Costa Rica with monolingual adults.<ref name=e18/> The language is also known by its dialect names Chirripó, Estrella, Telire, and Ujarrás.<ref name="e18" />
== History == Cabécar is considered to be one of a few "Chibcha-speaking tribes," categorized by similarities in the languages that they speak. Other Chibcha speaking tribes include the [[Bribri people|Bribri]] and the [[Boruca]], also of Costa Rica. It is believed that the languages of the Chibcha speaking tribes shared a common ancestor around 8,000 years ago. However, differences in the languages are thought to have come about from the influence of outside people, including influences from [[Mesoamerica]]. <ref name= "journal">{{cite journal|last1=Barrantes|first1=R.|last2=Smouse|first2=P.E.|last3=Mohrenweiser|first3=H.W.|last4=Gershowitz|first4=H.|last5=Azofeifa|first5=J.|last6=Arias|first6=T.D.|last7=Neel|first7=J.V.|title=Microevolution in Lower Central America: Genetic Characterization of the Chibcha-Speaking Groups of Costa Rica and Panama, and a Consensus Taxonom Based on Genetic and Linguistic Affinity|journal=American Journal of Human Genetics|date=1990|volume=43|pages=63-84}}</ref>
==Geographic Distribution== Cabécar is an endangered language spoken in Costa Rica. It is spoken by the [[Cabécar people]], an indigenous group located near the [[Cordillera de Talamanca|Talamancan mountains]] of Costa Rica. <ref name="journal" /> === Dialects/Varieties === There are two different dialects of Cabécar, each of which has more narrow dialects within it. One of these is spoken in the north, while the other is spoken in southern parts of Costa Rica. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Margery-Peña|first1=Enrique|last2=Constenla-Umaña|first2=Adolfo|title=Cabécar, Costa Rica|url=https://mpi-lingweb.shh.mpg.de/numeral/Cabecar.htm|publisher=University of Costa Rica|date=16 February 2010}}</ref>
==Phonology== Cabécar uses a Latin alphabet with [[Umlaut (diacritic)|umlaut]]s for (ë, ö), and [[tilde]]s for (ã, ẽ, ĩ, õ, ũ).<ref name="third">[http://www.native-languages.org/cabecar_guide.htm Native-languages.org]</ref> Cabécar has twelve [[vowels]], five of which are [[Nasal vowel|nasalized]].<ref name="third" />
