'''Sumo''' (also known as '''Sumu''') is the collective name for a group of [[Misumalpan]] languages spoken in [[Nicaragua]] and [[Honduras]]. Hale & Salamanca (2001) classify the Sumu languages into a northern Mayangna, composed of the Tawahka and Panamahka dialects, and southern Ulwa. Sumu specialist [[Kenneth L. Hale|Ken Hale]] considered the differences between Ulwa and Mayangna in both vocabulary and morphology to be so considerable that he prefers to speak of Ulwa as a language distinct from the northern Sumu varieties.

